4. Project Architecture
The application follows a microservices-inspired architecture deployed inside a Kubernetes cluster:
Architecture Flow:
•	User Browser sends HTTP requests to the Frontend Service (NodePort)
•	Frontend (React + Nginx) is served by 2 pods for redundancy
•	Frontend communicates with Backend via Backend Service (ClusterIP)
•	Backend (Node.js + Express) runs in 2 pods with auto-scaling up to 5
•	Backend connects to MongoDB Atlas (cloud database) for data storage
•	Prometheus scrapes metrics from all pods every 30 seconds
•	Grafana reads from Prometheus and displays real-time dashboards
•	Alertmanager fires alerts when pod health or resources are abnormal
Kubernetes Namespace Structure:
Namespace	Components
bookstore	Frontend Deployment (2 pods), Backend Deployment (2 pods), Services, HPA
default	Prometheus, Grafana, Alertmanager, Kube State Metrics, Node Exporter

 
5. Step-by-Step Implementation
PHASE 1: Cloning and Setting Up the Application
Step 1: Clone the Repository
The MERN stack bookstore application was cloned from GitHub using a sparse checkout to avoid downloading node_modules (which were accidentally committed to the repo):
git clone --depth 1 --filter=blob:none --sparse https://github.com/ADHITHYAAMARAGONDA/BOOK-STORE.git
cd BOOK-STORE
git sparse-checkout set backend frontend
Why sparse checkout? The repository had node_modules committed (1192 objects), making a normal clone extremely slow. Sparse checkout downloads only the backend/ and frontend/ folders we actually need.
Step 2: Install Dependencies and Test Locally
Before Dockerizing, we verified the application works locally:
cd backend
npm install mongoose express cors bcryptjs jsonwebtoken dotenv
node --dns-result-order=ipv4first index.js
Why --dns-result-order=ipv4first? Node.js v24 has a change in DNS resolution order that caused issues with MongoDB Atlas SRV records. This flag forces IPv4 DNS resolution first, which fixes the connection issue.
The backend runs on PORT 5555 as defined in config.js. The frontend runs on PORT 5173 (Vite default).
 
PHASE 2: Dockerization
Step 3: Create Backend Dockerfile
A Dockerfile is a script that tells Docker how to build a container image for the application. It defines the base image, working directory, dependencies, and startup command.
Backend Dockerfile (backend/Dockerfile):
FROM node:18-alpine
WORKDIR /app
COPY package*.json ./
RUN npm install
COPY . .
EXPOSE 5555
CMD ["node", "--dns-result-order=ipv4first", "index.js"]
Explanation of each line:
•	FROM node:18-alpine — Uses Node.js 18 on Alpine Linux (lightweight, only 5MB base image)
•	WORKDIR /app — Sets the working directory inside the container
•	COPY package*.json ./ — Copies package files first (Docker layer caching optimization)
•	RUN npm install — Installs all dependencies inside the container
•	COPY . . — Copies all source code into the container
•	EXPOSE 5555 — Declares the port the app listens on
•	CMD — The command to run when the container starts
Step 4: Create Frontend Dockerfile
The frontend uses a multi-stage build — first builds the React app, then serves it with Nginx (a lightweight web server):
Frontend Dockerfile (frontend/Dockerfile):
FROM node:18-alpine AS build
WORKDIR /app
COPY package*.json ./
RUN npm install
COPY . .
RUN npm run build

FROM nginx:alpine
COPY --from=build /app/dist /usr/share/nginx/html
EXPOSE 80
CMD ["nginx", "-g", "daemon off;"]
Why multi-stage build? The first stage (node:18-alpine) builds the React app into static files. The second stage (nginx:alpine) serves those static files. This makes the final image much smaller because Node.js is not included in the final image — only Nginx and the built HTML/CSS/JS files.
Step 5: Create .dockerignore Files
Created .dockerignore in both backend/ and frontend/ folders to prevent node_modules from being copied into the Docker image (we install them fresh inside Docker):
node_modules
.env
Step 6: Build and Push Docker Images
Built Docker images locally and pushed them to Docker Hub (a public container registry):
docker login
docker build -t adhithya143/bookstore-backend:v1 ./backend
docker push adhithya143/bookstore-backend:v1
docker build -t adhithya143/bookstore-frontend:v1 ./frontend
docker push adhithya143/bookstore-frontend:v1
Why Docker Hub? Kubernetes needs to pull container images from a registry. Docker Hub is free and publicly accessible. When Kubernetes deploys pods, it pulls the images from Docker Hub automatically.
 
PHASE 3: Kubernetes Deployment
Step 7: Start Minikube
Minikube creates a local single-node Kubernetes cluster inside Docker:
minikube start --driver=docker --memory=4096 --cpus=2
Why Minikube? For learning and development, we use Minikube instead of a real cloud cluster (AWS EKS, GCP GKE). It gives us a full Kubernetes environment on our laptop for free.
Step 8: Create Kubernetes Namespace
A namespace is a virtual cluster inside Kubernetes that isolates our bookstore resources from other applications:
# k8s/namespace.yaml
apiVersion: v1
kind: Namespace
metadata:
  name: bookstore

kubectl apply -f k8s/namespace.yaml
Step 9: Deploy Backend
The backend-deployment.yaml creates a Deployment (manages pods) and a Service (network access to pods):
•	Deployment: Runs 2 replicas of the backend pod for redundancy
•	Service (ClusterIP): Exposes the backend internally within the cluster on port 5555
•	Resource limits: CPU max 500m (0.5 cores), Memory max 256Mi
•	Resource requests: CPU 100m, Memory 128Mi (guaranteed minimums)
Step 10: Deploy Frontend
The frontend-deployment.yaml deploys the React app served by Nginx:
•	Deployment: Runs 2 replicas of the frontend pod
•	Service (NodePort): Exposes the frontend externally so users can access it from browser
•	Port 80: Nginx serves the React app on port 80 inside the container
Step 11: Configure Horizontal Pod Autoscaler (HPA)
HPA automatically scales the number of backend pods based on CPU usage:
•	minReplicas: 2 — always keeps at least 2 backend pods running
•	maxReplicas: 5 — can scale up to 5 pods when traffic increases
•	averageUtilization: 70 — scales up when CPU exceeds 70%
Why HPA? In real production, traffic is unpredictable. HPA ensures the app can handle sudden traffic spikes by automatically adding more pods, and scales back down when traffic reduces to save resources.
Step 12: Apply All Kubernetes Manifests
kubectl apply -f k8s/namespace.yaml
kubectl apply -f k8s/backend-deployment.yaml
kubectl apply -f k8s/frontend-deployment.yaml
kubectl apply -f k8s/hpa.yaml
kubectl get pods -n bookstore
 
PHASE 4: Monitoring with Prometheus and Grafana
Step 13: Install kube-prometheus-stack via Helm
Helm is the package manager for Kubernetes (like npm for Node.js). The kube-prometheus-stack Helm chart installs Prometheus, Grafana, and Alertmanager together in one command:
helm repo add prometheus-community https://prometheus-community.github.io/helm-charts
helm repo update
helm install monitoring prometheus-community/kube-prometheus-stack --namespace monitoring --create-namespace
This single command installs: Prometheus Operator, Prometheus Server, Grafana, Alertmanager, Node Exporter (hardware metrics), Kube State Metrics (Kubernetes object metrics).
Step 14: Access Grafana Dashboard
kubectl port-forward svc/monitoring-grafana 3000:80
Port-forwarding tunnels traffic from localhost:3000 to the Grafana service inside the cluster. Grafana credentials: admin / prom-operator.
Imported Kubernetes Pod dashboard (ID: 15760) which shows real-time metrics for all pods in the bookstore namespace including CPU usage, memory usage, pod status, and resource requests/limits.
Step 15: Access Prometheus
kubectl port-forward svc/prometheus-operated 9090:9090
Prometheus is accessible at http://localhost:9090. Used PromQL query to verify bookstore pod monitoring:
container_memory_usage_bytes{namespace="bookstore"}
This query returned real-time memory usage for all 4 bookstore pods (2 backend + 2 frontend), confirming Prometheus is successfully scraping metrics.
Step 16: Configure Alert Rules
Created custom Prometheus alert rules for the bookstore application (k8s/alertmanager-rules.yaml):
•	PodDown Alert: Fires when any pod in the bookstore namespace is not ready for more than 1 minute
•	HighMemoryUsage Alert: Fires when any pod consumes more than 200MB of memory
•	HighCPUUsage Alert: Fires when CPU usage exceeds 80% for more than 1 minute
kubectl apply -f k8s/alertmanager-rules.yaml

 
6. Key Demonstrations
6.1 Self-Healing Demo
This is the most important Kubernetes demonstration. When pods are forcefully deleted, Kubernetes automatically recreates them:
# Delete both backend pods
kubectl delete pod -l app=backend -n bookstore

# Immediately check - new pods already being created
kubectl get pods -n bookstore
Result: Within 10 seconds, Kubernetes automatically created 2 brand new backend pods to replace the deleted ones. The frontend continued running without any interruption. This demonstrates Kubernetes self-healing capability.
