9. Viva Questions & Answers
Q1: What is Docker and why did you use it?
Docker is a containerization platform that packages an application and all its dependencies into a container. A container is a lightweight, standalone, executable package that includes everything needed to run the application: code, runtime, libraries, and configuration.
We used Docker because: (1) It eliminates the 'works on my machine' problem, (2) Containers are portable — run on any OS, (3) Kubernetes requires containerized applications to manage them.
Q2: What is Kubernetes and what problem does it solve?
Kubernetes (K8s) is an open-source container orchestration platform that automates deployment, scaling, and management of containerized applications. It solves problems like: (1) Self-healing — automatically restarts crashed containers, (2) Auto-scaling — adds/removes pods based on load, (3) Load balancing — distributes traffic across pods, (4) Rolling updates — deploys new versions without downtime.
Q3: What is a Pod in Kubernetes?
A Pod is the smallest deployable unit in Kubernetes. It contains one or more containers that share the same network namespace and storage. In our project, each pod contains one container — either the bookstore backend or frontend. We run 2 replicas of each for high availability.
Q4: What is a Deployment in Kubernetes?
A Deployment is a Kubernetes object that manages a set of identical pods. It ensures the desired number of pod replicas are always running. If a pod crashes, the Deployment automatically creates a new one to replace it. We created two Deployments — one for backend (2 replicas) and one for frontend (2 replicas).
Q5: What is the difference between ClusterIP and NodePort services?
ClusterIP: Exposes the service only within the cluster. Used for internal communication between pods (e.g., frontend talking to backend). NodePort: Exposes the service on a static port on each node, accessible from outside the cluster. Used for the frontend service so users can access the bookstore from their browser.
Q6: What is HPA (Horizontal Pod Autoscaler)?
HPA automatically scales the number of pod replicas based on CPU or memory usage. In our project, the backend HPA is configured with minReplicas=2, maxReplicas=5, and CPU target=70%. If backend CPU exceeds 70%, Kubernetes automatically adds more backend pods (up to 5) to handle the load.
Q7: What is Prometheus and how does it work?
Prometheus is an open-source monitoring and alerting toolkit. It works by scraping (pulling) metrics from configured targets at regular intervals (every 30 seconds in our setup). It stores metrics as time-series data. In our project, Prometheus scrapes metrics from all Kubernetes pods, nodes, and the Kubernetes API server itself.
Q8: What is Grafana and how is it connected to Prometheus?
Grafana is an open-source visualization platform that creates dashboards from various data sources. It connects to Prometheus as a data source and uses PromQL (Prometheus Query Language) to query metrics. We imported dashboard ID 15760 which automatically creates panels for CPU, memory, pod status, and resource usage.
Q9: What is Helm and why did you use it?
Helm is the package manager for Kubernetes, similar to npm for Node.js or apt for Linux. It allows you to install complex Kubernetes applications with a single command using pre-configured Helm charts. We used the kube-prometheus-stack Helm chart which installs Prometheus, Grafana, and Alertmanager together automatically.
Q10: What is self-healing in Kubernetes? Can you demonstrate it?
Self-healing is Kubernetes' ability to automatically detect and recover from failures. When a pod crashes or is deleted, the Deployment controller detects the discrepancy between desired state (2 replicas) and actual state (1 replica) and immediately creates a new pod.
Demo: kubectl delete pod -l app=backend -n bookstore → kubectl get pods -n bookstore → New pods appear within 10 seconds automatically.
Q11: What are the alert rules you configured?
We configured three alert rules using PrometheusRule CRD: (1) PodDown — fires when any bookstore pod is not ready for more than 1 minute, (2) HighMemoryUsage — fires when memory exceeds 200MB, (3) HighCPUUsage — fires when CPU exceeds 80% for more than 1 minute.
Q12: What is the difference between Minikube and EKS?
Minikube is a local, single-node Kubernetes cluster for development and learning — it runs on your laptop for free. Amazon EKS (Elastic Kubernetes Service) is a managed Kubernetes service on AWS for production workloads — it runs on AWS infrastructure, supports multiple nodes, high availability, and integrates with AWS services like ALB, EBS, and IAM.

 
